Confounding and Collinearity

2025-06-12

This notebook walks through confounding and collinearity using an example involving childrens reading scores, shoe size, height, and age.

Setup

First, well load the necessary packages and generate our fake dataset of 200 children aged 618.

library(tidyverse)
##  Attaching core tidyverse packages  tidyverse 2.0.0 
##  dplyr     1.1.4      readr     2.1.5
##  forcats   1.0.0      stringr   1.5.1
##  ggplot2   3.5.2      tibble    3.2.1
##  lubridate 1.9.4      tidyr     1.3.1
##  purrr     1.0.4     
##  Conflicts  tidyverse_conflicts() 
##  dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
##  dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
##  Use the conflicted package (<http://conflicted.r-lib.org/>) to force all conflicts to become errors
library(broom)
set.seed(42)

# 1. Generate data
n <- 200
df <- tibble(
  Age = runif(n, 6, 18),                # ages between 6 and 18 years
  Height = 90 + 6 * Age + rnorm(n, 0, 5),   # height increases with age
  ShoeSize = 15 + 0.4 * Height + rnorm(n, 0, 2), # shoe size correlates with height
  ReadingScore = 30 + 5 * Age + rnorm(n, 0, 10)  # reading ability increases with age
)

1. Exploring Raw Correlations

Next, well peek at the correlations to see how these variables vary together. (Remember, seeing a correlation doesnt mean one thing /causes/ the other.)

df %>%
  select(Age, Height, ShoeSize, ReadingScore) %>%
  cor() %>%
  round(2)
##               Age Height ShoeSize ReadingScore
## Age          1.00   0.97     0.95         0.88
## Height       0.97   1.00     0.98         0.84
## ShoeSize     0.95   0.98     1.00         0.83
## ReadingScore 0.88   0.84     0.83         1.00

Then well plot shoe size versus reading score to visualize onne of these associations:

# Plot: ShoeSize vs ReadingScore
ggplot(df, aes(x = ShoeSize, y = ReadingScore)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = 'Reading Score vs. Shoe Size', x = 'Shoe Size', y = 'Reading Score')

At this point, one might (wrongly) think: Wow, bigger shoe sizes lead to better reading! But we havent accounted for age yet.

2. Illustrating Confounding by Age

A confounder influences both our predictor (shoe size) and outcome (reading score). Here, Age might actually account for the fact that kids both have larger feet and are better readers.

First, lets plot Age against ShoeSize:

ggplot(df, aes(x = Age, y = ShoeSize)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = 'Shoe Size vs. Age', x = 'Age (years)', y = 'Shoe Size')

Now lets adjust for Age by adding it into our regression with ShoeSize:

model_adjusted <- lm(ReadingScore ~ ShoeSize + Age, data = df)
tidy(model_adjusted)
## # A tibble: 3  5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)   33.5      13.8       2.42  1.63e- 2
## 2 ShoeSize      -0.140     0.264    -0.530 5.97e- 1
## 3 Age            5.59      0.650     8.61  2.35e-15

Youll see that once Age is included, the effect of ShoeSize often shrinks or vanishes. This shows how confounding can produce a spurious correlation.

3. Demonstrating Collinearity

Collinearity can have a similar effect, but through a different mechanism. Collinearity happens when predictors correlate strongly with each other, making it hard to distinguish their individual effects. Here weve set up height and shoe size to be correlated (but its not the case that either one causes the other, or reading scores, directly).

Lets look at Height vs.ShoeSize:

ggplot(df, aes(x = Height, y = ShoeSize)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = 'Height vs. Shoe Size', x = 'Height (cm)', y = 'Shoe Size')

Next, we fit a model with both ShoeSize and Height (without Age) to see the instability:

model_collinear <- lm(ReadingScore ~ ShoeSize + Height, data = df)
tidy(model_collinear)
## # A tibble: 3  5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic    p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept) -44.8        9.32     -4.81  0.00000301
## 2 ShoeSize      0.0742     0.425     0.175 0.862     
## 3 Height        0.794      0.170     4.67  0.00000554

Notice how coefficient signs or their uncertainty can flip aroundan indicator of multicollinearity.

4. Putting It All Together

Finally, well include Age, Height, and ShoeSize in one model:

model_full <- lm(ReadingScore ~ ShoeSize + Height + Age, data = df)
summary(model_full)

And then compare all four approaches side by side:

bind_rows(
  tidy(lm(ReadingScore ~ ShoeSize, df))       %>% mutate(model = '1. ShoeSize only'),
  tidy(model_adjusted)                       %>% mutate(model = '2. + Age'),
  tidy(model_collinear)                      %>% mutate(model = '3. ShoeSize + Height'),
  tidy(model_full)                           %>% mutate(model = '4. Full model')
) %>%
  select(model, term, estimate, std.error, statistic, p.value) %>%
  print(n = Inf)
## # A tibble: 12  6
##    model                term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##    <chr>                <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
##  1 1. ShoeSize only     (Intercept) -70.5       7.90      -8.93  2.94e-16
##  2 1. ShoeSize only     ShoeSize      2.01      0.0979    20.6   5.28e-51
##  3 2. + Age             (Intercept)  33.5      13.8        2.42  1.63e- 2
##  4 2. + Age             ShoeSize     -0.140     0.264     -0.530 5.97e- 1
##  5 2. + Age             Age           5.59      0.650      8.61  2.35e-15
##  6 3. ShoeSize + Height (Intercept) -44.8       9.32      -4.81  3.01e- 6
##  7 3. ShoeSize + Height ShoeSize      0.0742    0.425      0.175 8.62e- 1
##  8 3. ShoeSize + Height Height        0.794     0.170      4.67  5.54e- 6
##  9 4. Full model        (Intercept)  40.7      14.8        2.75  6.46e- 3
## 10 4. Full model        ShoeSize      0.237     0.382      0.621 5.35e- 1
## 11 4. Full model        Height       -0.297     0.218     -1.36  1.75e- 1
## 12 4. Full model        Age           6.49      0.926      7.01  3.77e-11

Youll find that Age remains the noteable predictor, while the apparent effects of height and shoe size weaken.

A word of warning: Even when we include all of three of these predictors in our model, there could be /other/ omitted variables, so its best to avoid any causal conclusions. Its hard to tease out cause and effect from observational data alone!

Recap of Concepts

  1. Confounder: A variable (e.g., Age) that drives both predictor and outcome, misleading simple associations.
  2. Collinearity: When predictors (e.g., Height & ShoeSize) correlate strongly, causing unstable coefficient estimates.
  3. Omitted Variable Bias: Even after adjusting, unmeasured factors can still bias estimates; causal claims require rigorous design (e.g., randomization).
